Starting out in R

R is both a programming language and an interactive environment for data exploration, statistics and computing. The easiest way to get started with R is by using the graphic interface RStudio. The main way of working with R is the console, where you enter commands and view results. RStudio surrounds this with various conveniences:

  • Console panel for sending R commands;
  • Text editor panel where R commands can be recorded for future reference;
  • Environment panel with a list of variables, which contain values that R has been told to save from previous commands;
  • File manager panel;
  • Help panel on the functions available in R;
  • Plots panel.
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Generic view of the different panels of the RStudio graphic interface.

S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Starting point: the working directory

R is always pointed at a specific directory on your computer, the working directory. The command for setting a working directory is setwd().

# set the working directory
setwd("the_path_to_my_working_folder")

Check out the help panel.

# get help on get or set working directory
`?`(setwd)
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Load and install packages

There are more than 10,000 of packages available to expand R. To see the list of installed packages type library(). The same command is used for loading a specific package into the workspace, making it available for the session.

# loads the package raster
library(sp)

# removes package from current workspace
detach(package:sp)

# install a package
install.packages("sp", dependencies = TRUE)
devtools::install_github("ropensci/rnaturalearthhires")

Variables and objects

All data structures and functions are objects in R.

# list all objects contained in the current workspace
ls()

We can assign data structures and functions to objects using the assignment operator ‘<-’
RStudio helpfully shows us the variable in the Environment pane.

# assign a value to a new object named 'myNewObject'
myNewObject <- 19535
myNewObject
## [1] 19535
# list all objects contained in the current workspace
ls()
## [1] "myNewObject"
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

We can remove objects from the workspace using rm().

# removes one object from R environment
rm(myNewObject)
ls()
## character(0)
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Naming objects

There is no naming convention. Even in the same package, multiple conventions might be used simultaneously. But usually, its advisable to stay consistent. Basically, there are five naming conventions to chose from:

  • lowercase (e.g., adjustcolor);
  • period.separated (e.g., plot.new);
  • underscore_separated (e.g., numeric_version);
  • lowerCamelCase (e.g., addTaskCallback) ***;
  • UpperCamelCase (e.g., SignatureMethod).
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Data types and structures

R distinguishes five basic data types.

# character
speciesName <- "Laminaria ochroleuca"

# integer (subset of real numbers)
bladeSize <- 41

# numeric (allows decimals)
bladeSize <- 41.4

# factor
demographicTraits <- factor("juvenil", levels = c("spore", "juvenil", "adult"))

# boolean
kelpSpecies <- TRUE
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

R object types differ in complexity. Vectors, matrices and arrays can only contain one data type.

Missing values are as NA (Not Available).
e.g., In a dataset with daily weather measurements over a longer period of time. On one day, the batteries of the weather station were empty and no measurements were taken. For integrity reasons, empty entries will still be stored in the data set but will be assigned the missing value ‘NA’.

myVector <- c(1, 5, 2, NA, 10, 4, NA, 7)
mean(myVector)
## [1] NA
mean(myVector, na.rm = T)
## [1] 4.833333
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Indexing

Each element of an object type is internally assigned an index (positive integer address) and you can retrieve single elements or a subset objects with these indices. Square brackets are used for indexing. In data frames (and lists) we can access columns using the ‘$’ operator.

# produce a sequence vector
x <- seq(5, 10, by = 1)

# retrieve the 3rd element of the vector x
x[3]
## [1] 7
# use address sequences
x[3:4]
## [1] 7 8
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

# use address vectors
x[c(1, 4, 6)]
## [1]  5  8 10
# use address negative vector integers
x[-c(1, 3:4)]
## [1]  6  9 10
myMatrix
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    1    4    7   10
## [2,]    2    5    8   11
## [3,]    3    6    9   12
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

# retrieve the matrix element located in the 1st row and 2nd column
myMatrix[1, 2]
## [1] 4
# retrieve the matrix element located in the 3rd row and 1st column
myMatrix[3, 1]
## [1] 3
# retrieve the data.frame element located in the 1st row and 1st column
courseSchedule[1, 1]
## [1] 1

# retrieve the 1st row of a data.frame
courseSchedule[1, ]
##   week  time day

Modifying elements by index location

The index of an element can be used to modify objects at specific locations

# Generate a data.frame
mySurvey <- data.frame(kelp = 5, seagrass = 10, coral = 1, fish = 20)
mySurvey
##   kelp seagrass coral fish
## 1    5       10     1   20
mySurvey[1] <- 100
mySurvey["seagrass"] <- 0

mySurvey
##   kelp seagrass coral fish
## 1  100        0     1   20

Functions

Functions are the basic foundations of R. From opening datasets to produce complex models and plots.
Functions have an argument list that can be empty (default terms) or have multiple expression terms.

# print character strings
print("Hello world!")
## [1] "Hello world!"
# join character strings
paste("Hello", "world", "!")
## [1] "Hello world !"
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

# determine the mean of a vector
myData <- c(2, 4, 3, 2, 3, 4, 2, 2)
mean(myData)
## [1] 2.75
# random numbers drawn from a given distribution without replacement
sample(1:30, size = 5)
## [1] 17 24 30 21 14
# random numbers drawn from a given distribution without replacement
sample(1:10, size = 5, replace = FALSE)
## [1] 9 5 7 1 3

Data import and export

R offers several options for accessing different data formats. Standard formats include text files, R files (single objects or entire workspaces), and databases. These data can be read in from files using a file path, but also from the Internet using an URL path or from the clipboard.

# list all files in your folder
list.files()

# reading data frames from comma delimited files
myDF <- read.table("courseSchedule.txt")
myDF <- read.table("courseSchedule.txt", sep = ",", header = T)

# reading data frames from excel files
library(gdata)
read.xls("courseSchedule.xlsx", sheet = 1)
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

# data frames can be written to files using e.g write.table
mySpeciesSurvey <- data.frame(Location = c("San Luiz", "La marchila"), Lon = c(25.45, 85.41), 
    Lat = c(33.28, 25.21))
Location Lon Lat
San Luiz 25.45 33.28
La marchila 85.41 25.21 
write.table(mySpeciesSurvey, "mySpeciesSurvey.txt", row.names = F, col.names = T, sep = ";", 
    dec = ".")
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Objects available in the environment can also be saved (“.RData file”).

# save objects to external file
myData <- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
save(myData, file = "path-to-data.RData")

# load object from external file
load("path-to-data.RData")

# save all objects in the environment to external file
save.image(myData, file = "path-to-data.RData")
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Reading and writing R scripts

It is crucial to record the way scripts were performed so we can reproduce them later. The usual workflow is to save your code in an R script (“.R file”).

You can go to “File/New File/R Script” to create a new R script. These files can be sourced in additional scripts to create clean pipelines. To effectively execute R expressions available in the script editor, use the most important keyboard shortcuts: Cmd/Ctrl + Enter.

# source external file
source("path-to-script.R")

# load objects from external file
load(file = "path-to-data.RData")
S1 // Brief recap on R computing basics

Commenting the code

Add comments to pipelines, using lines starting with the # character. This makes it easier to follow the code.

# generate a vector
myData <- c(32, 3, 5, 4, 778, 4, 3, 5, 7, 4)

# calculate the mean
mean(myData)

# subset my data.frame
myData <- myData[myData < quantile(myData, 0.95), ]
